  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3090" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Sens, April 13, 1892.</dateline>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi> Schuchardt,</opener>
        <p>I was much pleased to find a letter from you at the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.3096">Poste Restante</ref> here this morning - we have had in France an April without precedent in living memory, and I hope the weather has been equally aimiable on the north shore of Garda. I came on monday for a fortnight in the Yonne, and stayed an hour and three quarters at Melun on the way. In the museum of the Cathedral here they have the mitre and mass robes of S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi> Thomas a Becket who lived at S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi> Columbos convent just outside this metropolitical city for the three years before his assassination in Canterbury Cathedral: I went thither yesterday, but found the place occupied by a modern nunnery with however a beautiful new Gothic chapel by an architect of this place, in which three or four sculptured fragments of the medieval chapel are preserved. This is a nice place to be quite quiet in, though it is not depressing like some provincial towns - Some of the place names in the department look in their modern form like <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref> e. g. Yrouerre, Irancy, Beru<note n="1"
            place="foot" type="editorial">Heute: <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6093">Bery</placeName>.</note>, Sarri<note n="2" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Heute: <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.1">Sarry</placeName>.</note>, etc: etc: But the most Basque of French departments omitting those on the Spanish Frontier is, as I told you in 89, that of the <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Aisne</hi>, where even the medieval forms look <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Euskarian</ref>. I have long urged the Basques to bring out a catena nova librorum Euskarorum vetustiorum - M<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>
          <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5682">A. D’Abbadie</persName>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">might do</hi> much with his own wealth and by his influence with the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.443">
French Academy</ref>. You do not mention specifically the receipt of <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5712">Inchauspes</persName>

          <bibl>Dante Canto primo</bibl> - You will have noticed if it reached you, with a new Biscayan devotional tomelet, that the line <foreign
            xml:lang="it">“risposi lui con vergognosa fronte“</foreign> is not translated at all, and that the lines <foreign
            xml:lang="it">“con la paura ch’uscia di sua vista”</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="it">“tu sei <hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">solo</hi> colei da cui io tolsi”</foreign>, and <foreign
              xml:lang="it">“<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">vedrai</hi> gli antichi spiriti dolenti”</foreign>, are incorrectly or incompletely translated. A few lines in Basque from you to <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5712">Inchauspe</persName> might encourage him to go on. M<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>
          <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1466">W. J. Van Eys</persName> lives at Braia (Genoese for farm house, Basque Borda (perhaps Roumanian <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Bordei</hi>) Van Eys, San Remo, Provinzia di Porto Maurizio. The fables of <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5715">Goyetche</persName> are very badly <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">punctuated</hi> - <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1620">Pierre Goyetche</persName>, in whose house at <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.1">
Sare</placeName> you and I occupied the rooms of the Prince of Bascophiles, told me that their author was his uncle, the curé of Urrugne. <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.3138">The Revue Critique</ref> of last year <pb
            facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/> contains a brief notice of <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2939">Vinsons</persName> Bibliography by a sublibrarian of the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5043">
Sorbonne</ref> who knows no Basque. M<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>
          <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5716">Chatelain</persName> the secretary of the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5047">Hautes Etudes</ref> and Editor of the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5717">Revue des Bibliothèques</ref> has consented to my publishing in the latter periodical, probably next month, a fuller attack on the Vinsonian muddles. I should like to see your article thereon. I have read or heard somewhere that <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">bai</hi>
          </foreign> is used in parts of Ireland to mean <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">yes</hi> as in Basque. I have long supposed Corcach to be Basque <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Kolkoak</hi> as it is on a large and much indented gulf or bay. an old Irish name for Connemara, or part of it, seems to me to contain the Basque element which would be suitable to that coast and to the lake-bosoms of its interior. I have hitherto attached Basque <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Ehun</hi>
          </foreign> to Gothic <foreign xml:lang="got">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">hunda</hi>
          </foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="la">centum</foreign>, but can it be related to <foreign
            xml:lang="eu">aevum</foreign>, <foreign
            xml:lang="el">ἀιων</foreign> an age, then specifically a period of 100 years? <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5712">Inchauspes</persName> word <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">maina</hi> for “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">studio</hi>” puzzles me - Can he be thinking of table, meaning study-table? if so it is incorrect. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1062">Azkues</persName> grammar is I think a dangerous book. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2047">
Linschmann</persName> would I feel sure lend you the books of our Society, which you ought to join. Spain having no means of sending money by postal order to any forane contry injures herself and irritates all the civilised world - Such civilization as she possesses seems to sit ill upon her. Can Basque <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">pikaina</hi>
          </foreign>, which I find used in the <ref
            target="http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/57312600">Exercicio Izpiritualac of Anavitarte 1880</ref> meaning tit-bits, or choicest morsels, be derived from English “<foreign xml:lang="en">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
pickings</hi>

          </foreign>” which we often use in the sense of “selections” of the best parts of anything as well as for the refuse left for the starving to pick up. You will be amused in a few days by my <bibl>“Helaine”</bibl> fragment in the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.3129">Revue de Linguistique</ref> if you see that publication. In the latest Edition of my supernumerary psalm I regret not having written <foreign
              xml:lang="eu">“Dauide<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">c</hi>” and “ahal<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">qu</hi>ea”</foreign>, <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">as I had the intention to do</hi>. I have sold myself 10 francs worth of the <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5712">Inchauspean</persName>
          <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.4219">Dante</persName> besides the 10 francs worth bought up by the author - if I sell 10 francs worth more I shall have recovered the cost of printing. The<note
            n="3" place="foot"
            type="editorial">
Fortsetzung am linken und danach am oberen Rand.</note> Dante Society of Cambridge, Massachusetts have promised to reprint it. I think we discussed at <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.42">Munich</placeName> the case of “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">en sin</hi>” in the <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Cuentu ñarigudu </hi>in the <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Olla Asturiana </hi>- I at first thought “<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">en</hi>” meant “<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">and</hi>” as in <foreign
            xml:lang="is">Icelandic</foreign> or <foreign
            xml:lang="nl">
Flemish</foreign>, but I suppose it goes with <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">sin</hi> and means “<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">in</hi> (a state of) <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">without</hi>”, the Basque <foreign xml:lang="eu">“<hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">gabean</hi>”</foreign>. I go to Auxerre on Monday and return to <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.666">Paris</placeName> on the 25<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi>. They call many of the streams in this department “<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ru</hi>”</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/>
        <p>
          <note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite</note>
          <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2939">Vinson</persName> says the <persName>
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Ostolaza</hi>
          </persName> belonged to <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5719">Antonio de Trueba</persName>, since whose death he has not heard what is become of that unique and most invaluable book.</p>
      </div>
